\end_inset

based on peers’ experiences
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the same sentence in double
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Such a system could affect outcomes through three channels:
 correcting farmers’ beliefs and reducing their uncertainty about seed performance (belief updating),
 helping farmers identify better dealers (dealer sorting),
 or inducing dealers to improve seed preservation (supply-side accountability)
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RESOLVED:
 Renamed the channel "supply-side accountability" to make the mechanism as specific as belief updating and dealer sorting,
 while avoiding the adverse-selection label.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We test this approach in a randomized controlled trial involving 3,500 farmers and 350 agro-dealers in the market for high-yielding maize seed in Uganda.
 We find that the intervention increases farmers’ perceptions of seed performance,
 leads to higher adoption of high-yielding maize seed,
 and raises yields by 13%.
 While there is some evidence of increased switching between dealers,
 this switching is not directed toward higher-rated dealers,
 and we find no improvement in dealer-level seed performance,
 providing little support for dealer sorting or supply-side accountability.
 The results point to belief updating as the primary mechanism.
 Consistent with this interpretation,
 effects on perceptions are larger among farmers without prior purchasing experience —
 those with the greatest uncertainty about seed performance.
\end_layout

