 We introduce a system that collects farmers’ evaluations of maize seed purchased from agro-dealers and aggregates them into ratings that summarize the experiences of multiple farmers facing similar conditions.
 These ratings are disseminated to both farmers and agro-dealers,
 providing a summary signal about seed performance at agro-dealers that individual farmers may find difficult to obtain through their own experimentation or social networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aggregated peer ratings address key limitations of existing approaches.
 They are based on farmers’ evaluations of experienced seed performance and therefore reflect performance under local conditions.
 They are disseminated directly to farmers,
 allowing the information to reach those who do not typically visit agro-dealers.
 The system is decentralized,
 relying less on institutional capacity.
 Importantly,
 the system does not measure or certify objective seed quality.
 It aggregates farmers' assessments of experienced performance —
 whether the seed they purchased yielded well,
 germinated reliably,
 and tolerated local conditions.
 These assessments may diverge from laboratory measures of seed purity or authenticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A rating system that aggregates and disseminates farmers' purchasing experiences could improve outcomes through several channels.
 First,
 farmers may hold imprecise or biased beliefs about seed performance.
 Disseminating aggregated peer experiences could reduce uncertainty among all farmers and,
 when priors are pessimistic relative to the signal,
 raise expected performance among farmers without prior purchasing experience,
 increasing adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 dealer-specific ratings could enable dealer sorting by revealing performance differences across sellers conditional on purchasing from agro-dealers.
 In agricultural input markets,
 farmers typically choose among a small number of local dealers with limited information about relative seed performance.
 When dealer-choice frictions are high relative to quality variation,
 consumers settle for suboptimal matches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stigler1961economics"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 By aggregating dispersed information about seller-specific performance,
 ratings enable the kind of sorting that characterizes online review platforms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/jel.48.4.935,luca2016reviews"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 If performance varies substantially across dealers,
 ratings could induce farmers to switch to higher-performing sellers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 the rating system could improve dealer-level seed performance through supply-side accountability.
 In the prevailing market equilibrium,
 agro-dealers may have weak incentives to invest in seed storage and handling because farmers cannot credibly assess seed performance at the point of purchase and may struggle to attribute later outcomes such as germination or yield to dealer behavior.
 By aggregating farmer experiences into visible ratings,
 the system creates bottom-up pressure on dealers:
 poor seed performance becomes reputationally costly,
 while better-preserved seed can attract future demand.
 The rating system can therefore shift competition toward quality by making dealer-level performance more observable to potential buyers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hasanain2019no,doi:10.1086/734133"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These three channels are not mutually exclusive,
 but they generate distinct empirical predictions that allow us to assess their relative importance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test this approach in a randomized controlled trial (RCT) involving approximately 3,500 smallholder farmers and 350 agro-dealers in the market for high-yielding maize seed in eastern Uganda.
 The randomized design allows us to estimate causal effects,
 while three rounds of detailed data enable us to understand how and why the intervention affects behavior.
 We track outcomes along the full causal chain,
 from farmers’ perceptions and adoption decisions to agricultural productivity.
 Additional data on farmers’ choice of agro-dealers,
 agro-dealer seed handling practices,
 and objective indicators of seed performance allow us to trace the channels through which the intervention operates;
 measures of dealer services and signaling provide secondary evidence on other dealer responses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exposure to peer ratings improves farmers’ perceptions of seed performance and increases adoption of high-yielding maize seed.
 Treated farmers achieve 13% higher yields,
 showing that the intervention has economically meaningful downstream effects.
 Because adoption and productivity effects are consistent with all three channels,
 channel identification rests on the outcomes that differ across the model's predictions.
 While there is some evidence that the intervention induces farmers to switch between sellers,
 this switching is not directed toward higher-rated dealers,
 providing little support for dealer sorting as a primary channel.
 Nor do we find improvements in dealer-level seed performance,
 providing little support for supply-side accountability as a primary channel.
 Consistent with belief updating,
 effects on perceptions are larger among farmers without prior purchasing experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper contributes to the literature on agricultural technology adoption,
 particularly on the role of input quality uncertainty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2023102424"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and farmers’ beliefs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We advance this literature in three ways.
 First,
 we introduce an intervention that addresses limitations of existing seed performance signals —
 it is decentralized,
 experience-based,
 and reaches farmers who do not engage with formal markets —
 and show that it improves adoption and productivity,
 with the pattern of results pointing to belief updating as the primary channel.
 Second,
 by tracking outcomes on both sides of the market —
 farmers' beliefs and switching behavior,
 and agro-dealers' seed handling practices and seed performance —
 we can assess the relative importance of belief updating,
 dealer sorting,
 and supply-side accountability.
 Together with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dar2020private"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 our study is among the few to connect farmer and agro-dealer perspectives,
 providing a more complete picture than studies focusing on buyers or sellers alone.
 Third,
 the pattern of results —
 positive effects on perceptions and adoption,
 undirected switching and no improvement in dealer-level seed performance —
 provides evidence that uncertainty about seed performance is a binding constraint on adoption in seed markets.
 While overly pessimistic or imprecise beliefs have been documented in fertilizer markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 we provide evidence of this mechanism in seed markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More broadly,
 this paper connects to a growing literature on crowd-sourced quality information,
 transparency,
 and search frictions in markets with hard-to-observe seller quality.
 Research on online review platforms documents that consumer feedback affects both sides of the market:
 buyers use reviews to make more informed choices,
 while sellers adjust their behavior in response to public quality signals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/0022051041409075,https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1756-2171.2006.tb00067.x,10.1257/jel.48.4.935,reimers2021digitization"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Related work shows that reducing search and information frictions can improve matching,
 trade,
 and market integration in both online and low-income-country markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NBERw28100,NBERw33221,Startz2024,NBERw33082,10.1093/ej/ueaf009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In many of these settings,
 an important channel is sorting:
 information helps buyers identify better sellers among many options.
 Our study shows that in a very different setting —
 a low-information,
 offline agricultural input market —
 crowd-sourced ratings need not operate primarily through seller choice.
 In our setting,
 the evidence points less to sorting across agro-dealers and more to belief updating about whether agro-dealer seed performs well relative to outside options.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hasanain2019no"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find a related null effect on switching in Pakistan,
 where crowd-sourced information on livestock insemination services does not induce farmers to switch providers.
\end_layout

