 continuous outcome,
 no ceiling effect),
 undirected switching (Prediction 4),
 and null effects on seed quality (Prediction 5).
 On the timing concern:
 the design accommodates all channels —
 ratings in T1,
 behavioral responses in T2,
 yield effects in T3.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Prediction 3 (Productivity).

\series default
 All three channels can raise yields if they increase adoption of genuinely higher-performing seed or improve the performance of seed actually purchased.
 Dealer sorting and supply-side accountability may additionally raise yields conditional on adopting —
 through sorting to better agro-dealers and through improved seed quality,
 respectively.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RESOLVED:
 Acknowledged that all channels work partly through adoption,
 with search cost and supply-side having additional pathways.
 Changed "matching" to "sorting."
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Productivity therefore does not discriminate sharply between channels.
 For belief updating,
 yield gains require that,
 on average,
 peer ratings move adoption decisions toward seed with higher true performance relative to outside options.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Prediction 4 (Switching).

\series default
 The three channels differ in their predictions about switching between agro-dealers.
 Under the belief-updating channel as defined here,
 peer ratings primarily shift beliefs about agro-dealer seed relative to outside options rather than reallocating farmers across specific agro-dealers;
 by itself,
 this channel therefore does not predict directed switching toward higher-rated dealers.
 Under the dealer sorting channel,
 dealer-specific ratings reveal performance differences,
 enabling farmers to switch to higher-rated dealers,
 predicting increased switching.
 The supply-side accountability channel has no direct prediction on switching.
 Finding that any increase in switching is not directed toward higher-rated dealers weakens evidence for dealer sorting as the primary channel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Prediction 5 (Seed performance)
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RESOLVED:
 Changed "quality" to "performance" for consistency with the model (θ_j = seed performance).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.

\series default
 The three channels differ in their predictions about objective seed performance.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RESOLVED:
 Standardized on "objective" throughout.
 Dropped "actual/true/real" variants.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Under belief updating,
 the intervention shifts beliefs but not seed performance at a given agro-dealer:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 is unchanged.
 Under dealer sorting,
 the intervention may change the performance of seed actually purchased by farmers if they reallocate toward higher-performing agro-dealers,
 but this operates through dealer choice rather than through product improvement at any given agro-dealer.
 Under the supply-side accountability channel,
 if agro-dealers respond to reputational incentives by investing in handling and storage,
 degradation 
\begin_inset Formula $d(e_{j})$
\end_inset

 falls and dealer-level seed performance 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 improves.
 Finding no treatment effect on dealer-level seed performance weakens evidence for the supply-side accountability channel,
 subject to measurement precision and timing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The channels may also differ in their predicted timing of effects.
 Belief updating and dealer sorting can affect behavior as soon as farmers receive ratings:
 beliefs may shift immediately,
 and dealer choices can adjust at the next purchase occasion.
 These effects may persist or evolve through endline as farmers accumulate own and peer experience.
 Supply-side accountability may take longer to affect farmer perceptions and adoption,
 because any dealer improvements in seed storage and handling must first translate into realized seed performance and then become observable to farmers through experience or updated ratings.
 This timing distinction is useful when interpreting whether effects appear first at midline,
 persist to endline,
 or emerge only after an additional rating cycle.
\end_layout

