\begin_layout Subsection
Randomization and power
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsection: Experimental design"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Randomization is conducted at the agro-dealer catchment-area level with equal assignment probability.
 Catchment areas consist of geographically proximate clusters of towns,
 villages,
 markets,
 trading centers,
 and other key hubs,
 and typically include several agro-dealers.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To define these areas,
 we used a haversine function to construct an adjacency matrix based on GPS coordinates,
 assigning agro-dealers less than five kilometers apart to the same catchment area.
 The five-kilometer threshold was selected based on a visual inspection of the map,
 the average village size in our sample,
 and the reported distance between farmers and agro-dealers in survey data from a previous study of the maize value chain,
 available 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/PIMMVC/tree/master/data/public"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fn:The-haversine-function"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Because the intervention changes the local information environment,
 treatment is assigned at the catchment-area level rather than within catchments.
 Farmer-level treatment effects are identified by comparing farmers in treated and control catchment areas.
 As described below,
 farmers were sampled from villages linked to agro-dealers in each catchment area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sample sizes were determined using simulation-based power calculations based on data from prior surveys,
 allowing power to be assessed under empirically relevant outcome distributions at both the farmer and agro-dealer levels.
 Full details are provided in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "pre-analysis plan"
target "https://www.socialscienceregistry.org/trials/6361"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (AEA RCT Registry,
 RCT ID 0006361).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Specifically,
 we used data from 78 agro-dealers and 1,529 smallholder farmers in their catchment areas,
 gathered from three districts in eastern Uganda in July 2019.
 These data are publicly accessible 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/PIMMVC/tree/master/data/public"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The simulations indicate that with more than 112 catchment areas,
 our experiment achieves 80% power to detect effects on a selection of primary outcomes.
 This corresponds to approximately 318 agro-dealers.
 Further simulations at the farm-household level guided our decision to sample ten farmers per agro-dealer,
 resulting in a total sample size of 3,180 households.
 These figures represent the minimum required sample size;
 the actual sample size,
 including the number of agro-dealers and farmers per treatment arm,
 is detailed in the Sample Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Sample"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second,
 randomizing at the individual agro-dealer level raises ethical concerns.
 When two or more agro-dealers operate in close proximity,
 treating only one could create unfair competitive advantages or disadvantages.
 Randomizing at the catchment area level mitigates this risk.
 Third,
 it reduces the likelihood of spillovers from treated to control agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

