\begin_layout Subsection
Perceived seed performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the first link in the causal chain:
 whether the clearinghouse shifts farmers’ perceptions of agro-dealer seed quality.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects of clearinghouse on farmer perceptions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports treatment effects on a perception index that combines farmer ratings of agro-dealer seed performance across six dimensions:
 general quality,
 yield,
 drought tolerance,
 pest and disease tolerance,
 maturity time,
 and germination (see Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "questions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

 for the exact questions used for measuring perceptions).
 The clearinghouse increases this index by 0.09 standard deviations,
 significant at the 10% level.
 The positive sign is consistent with the belief-updating channel in the model if the peer signal was more favorable than farmers' prior beliefs about agro-dealer seed performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These estimates should be interpreted with some caution.
 The perception index requires non-missing ratings on all six dimensions for at least one dealer,
 and ratings were collected from farmers in control catchment areas only at endline.
 Treatment effects on perceptions can therefore be estimated only for the final survey round and are less precise than estimates for the main adoption and productivity outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model also predicts stronger updating among farmers with greater prior uncertainty.
 We examine this prediction using prior agro-dealer seed-purchasing experience,
 proxied by whether the farmer used improved maize seed from an agro-dealer in the season preceding baseline.
 The subgroup estimates are similar:
 0.102 standard deviations among farmers without prior experience and 0.092 among prior purchasers,
 and a formal interaction test does not reject equality.
 We therefore interpret the perception results as evidence of upward belief updating overall,
 rather than as strong evidence of differential updating by prior experience.
\end_layout

