reference "Effects on farmer outcomes at end of causal chain: Adoption"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports treatment-control estimates of the clearinghouse effects on farmers' adoption and sourcing decisions.
 Consistent with the model's prediction that credible performance information can increase adoption by reducing decision-relevant uncertainty,
 the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 index of adoption outcomes is significantly higher for treated farmers than for control farmers at both midline and endline (
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.05$
\end_inset

).
 The response is concentrated on the extensive margin:
 treated farmers are more likely to source maize seed from agro-dealers,
 while quantities purchased conditional on buying do not differ significantly between treated and control farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Across all plots,
 treated farmers are six percentage points more likely than control farmers to purchase high-yielding maize seed from an agro-dealer at midline,
 equivalent to 18% of the baseline mean.
 By endline,
 the estimated agro-dealer sourcing effect is three percentage points and is no longer statistically significant,
 although treated farmers remain more likely than control farmers to adopt improved maize varieties in both survey rounds:
 3.5 percentage points at midline and 4.2 percentage points at endline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next examine the same sourcing margin on a randomly selected maize plot.
 Treated farmers are nearly five percentage points more likely at midline and 3.6 percentage points more likely at endline to obtain seed for the randomly selected plot from an agro-dealer.
 Seed expenditure on the plot is also significantly higher for treated farmers than for control farmers.
 These treatment-control differences are accompanied by reduced reliance on farmer-saved seed at midline.
 Estimated effects on individual hybrid and OPV variety categories are positive but imprecise.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We classify varieties as improved if they correspond to recognized hybrid or OPV types and the seed was newly purchased rather than recycled or farmer-saved.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 These results indicate that the intervention shifted farmers toward agro-dealer seed,
 but they do not by themselves distinguish whether this reflects belief updating,
 dealer sorting,
 or supply-side responses.
\end_layout

