\begin_layout Standard
We next examine whether increased farmer engagement is reflected at the agro-dealer level and consider various agro-business related outcomes (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on dealer outcomes at end of causal chain: Business volume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

).
 The outcomes include self-reported sales volume for the four most common high-yielding maize varieties in the previous season (Longe 7H,
 Longe 10H,
 Longe 4,
 and Longe 5),
 average start-of-season prices,
 implied revenue,
 the number of maize-seed customers served per day,
 and the number of maize varieties stocked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The agro-dealer level results are consistent with increased market activity observed at the farmer level.
 At midline,
 treated agro-dealers score significantly higher on the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 index,
 and their estimated revenue is nearly 20% higher than that of control agro-dealers,
 significant at the 10% level.
 This revenue effect appears more consistent with expanded sales than price increases,
 though the volume and price components are not individually statistically significant.
 At endline,
 the treatment effect on the business-activity index is significant at the 1% level,
 driven primarily by treated agro-dealers reporting 31% more customers than control agro-dealers,
 or roughly six additional customers per day relative to the baseline mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together,
 the farmer and dealer results suggest that the clearinghouse increased engagement with agro-dealer seed markets.
 Treated farmers became more likely than control farmers to purchase high-yielding seed from agro-dealers,
 and treated agro-dealers report higher customer activity and revenue than control agro-dealers.
 These effects are consistent with the model's adoption prediction,
 but because adoption and market activity can arise under all three channels,
 they are interpreted as downstream market responses rather than as evidence for a specific mechanism.
