\begin_layout Subsection
Harvest outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We examine harvest-related outcomes on a randomly selected maize plot in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on farmer outcomes at end of causal chain: Harvest"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Outcomes include production,
 plot size,
 yield,
 the value of maize production at market prices net of seed costs,
 maize retained for seed in the following season,
 and maize sales outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results show positive endline effects.
 The overall index is positive and statistically significant,
 and treated farmers achieve yields that are 56 kilograms per acre higher than the control group,
 a 13% increase relative to the baseline mean and significant at the 1% level.
 The value of maize production net of seed costs is 66,000 UGX higher for treated farmers,
 approximately 18 USD at the time of the survey.
 Treated farmers also retain less maize for seed at midline,
 consistent with reduced reliance on farmer-saved seed.
 We find no effects on quantity sold or total maize revenue.
 This suggests that the yield gains did not translate into detectable increases in marketed surplus,
 and that additional output was likely retained within the household.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The harvest effects provide downstream evidence that the intervention improved realized agricultural outcomes,
 not only beliefs or sourcing decisions.
 They are consistent with the model's prediction that credible seed-performance information can raise yields when it shifts farmers toward higher-performing seed or improves the performance of seed actually purchased.
 However,
 productivity effects do not distinguish sharply between belief updating,
 dealer sorting,
 and supply-side accountability,
 since all three channels can generate yield gains.
\end_layout

