\begin_layout Standard
A back-of-envelope calculation suggests that the adoption margin alone is unlikely to mechanically account for the full yield effect.
 Even assuming improved varieties yield 50 percent more than farmer-saved seed,
 the roughly 4 percentage point increase in agro-dealer sourcing would explain only a modest share of the observed 56 kg/acre yield gain.
 The remaining effect could reflect changes in how farmers use purchased seed.
 By reducing uncertainty about seed performance,
 the clearinghouse may increase incentives to invest in complementary inputs whose returns depend on seed quality,
 as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bulte2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Consistent with this explanation,
 treated farmers are approximately 5 percentage points more likely to use inorganic fertilizer at both midline and endline and are less likely to intercrop at midline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Alternative channels:
 dealer sorting and supply-side accountability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results so far are consistent with belief updating:
 the clearinghouse improves perceived seed performance and increases engagement with agro-dealer seed markets.
 However,
 as outlined in out model in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "2 Conceptual model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"
tuple "list"

\end_inset

,
 the downstream adoption and productivity effects could also arise through two other channels in the model.
 First,
 ratings may help farmers sort across agro-dealers.
 Second,
 public ratings may increase agro-dealers' incentives to improve the performance of the seed they sell.
 We therefore turn to these two alternative channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dealer sorting and agro-dealer switching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the clearinghouse provides agro-dealer-specific ratings,
 it may help farmers identify higher-performing sellers and reallocate purchases toward them.
 The model predicts that this channel should generate switching across agro-dealers,
 especially where ratings reveal meaningful cross-dealer differences.
 Unlike belief updating about agro-dealer seed in general,
 dealer sorting requires movement across sellers rather than only increased engagement with agro-dealer seed markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test this prediction by examining whether treated farmers are more likely to switch agro-dealers between adjacent seasons.
 The analysis is restricted to farmers who purchase maize seed from an agro-input shop in both seasons,
 since switching is only defined for repeated buyers.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "switchingfarmers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows that switching is common:
 46% of farmers who purchase maize seed in both baseline and midline buy from a different agro-dealer across the two seasons.
 The clearinghouse increases switching by 6.2 percentage points at midline,
 significant at the 10% level.
 By endline,
 the estimate is smaller and no longer statistically significant.
 Exploratory heterogeneity analyses by rating dispersion provide similarly limited support for dealer sorting:
 switching appears,
 if at all,
 only in catchment areas with unusually dispersed dealer ratings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results provide only weak evidence for dealer sorting as a primary channel.
 The intervention may have induced some short-run reallocation across sellers,
 but the effect is not persistent.
 Moreover,
 switching alone does not establish that farmers sorted toward higher-performing dealers,
 especially because the adoption and business-activity results point to broader engagement with agro-dealer seed markets.
 This interpretation is consistent with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hasanain2019no"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who find no evidence that livestock farmers switch to higher-performance veterinarians.
\end_layout

