\begin_layout Subsubsection
Supply-side accountability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next examine the supply-side accountability channel.
 In the model,
 public ratings increase the reputational return to selling well-performing seed.
 This channel has two empirical layers.
 First,
 dealers may respond when ratings make quality more visible,
 including through seed handling and storage practices,
 customer service,
 or quality signaling.
 Second,
 if these responses improve the seed itself,
 they should translate into measurable improvements in dealer-level seed performance.
 By contrast,
 belief updating changes farmers' perceptions and adoption decisions without changing seed performance at a given dealer.
 Evidence from other contexts shows that public quality disclosure can induce sellers to adjust behavior 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1162/003355303321675428,doi:10.1086/688875,doi:10.1086/734133"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with dealer practices and customer-facing responses.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on dealer efforts"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports effects on agro-dealer practices.
 We construct two indices from enumerator observations of seed handling and storage:
 labor-intensive practices,
 such as not storing seed in open containers,
 and capital-intensive practices,
 such as having a leak-proof roof.
 Neither of the two indices responds to the intervention.
 Thus,
 we find little evidence that the clearinghouse induced dealers to change the storage and handling practices most directly related to seed preservation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention does,
 however,
 generate suggestive evidence of customer-facing dealer responses.
 We measure service provision from both dealer and farmer reports.
 The dealer-reported service index,
 including recommendations about complementary inputs,
 is higher among treated dealers at endline;
 a parallel farmer-reported service index is higher for treated dealers at midline.
 Although the timing differs,
 both measures point to improved customer-facing service provision.
 We also find a positive effect on activities that signal credibility or professionalism to customers,
 such as membership in a professional association:
 a fifth index capturing signaling practices is higher among treated dealers at endline.
 These patterns suggest that dealers responded to increased transparency,
 especially along service and signaling margins.
\end_layout

