\begin_layout Standard
We then examine whether these dealer responses translated into measurable improvements in seed performance.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on bag of maize seed bought at dealer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports treatment effects on seed-performance indicators.
 Enumerators randomly purchased an original,
 sealed maize seed bag from agro-dealers and evaluated moisture content,
 packaging integrity,
 and packaging information,
 including the visibility of the packaging date and lot number and the number of days since packaging.
 We find no significant treatment effects on these indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because not all sampled agro-dealers had maize seed in stock,
 the seed-performance sample is smaller than the main dealer sample.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.9 Treatment effects on agro-dealers’ seed PERFORMANCE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports a power analysis for seed moisture content,
 the pre-registered objective measure,
 showing that the observed effect size would not be detectable even with a much larger sample.
 We therefore interpret the null estimates cautiously.
 As a robustness check,
 we also examine additional seed-performance indicators available for larger samples and again find no treatment effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together,
 the supply-side results show some evidence that dealers responded to increased transparency,
 primarily through customer-facing service and signaling margins.
 However,
 we do not find detectable improvements in seed handling,
 storage,
 or measured seed performance.
 The evidence therefore supports a limited supply-side response,
 but not the stronger version of supply-side accountability in which reputational pressure improves the underlying performance of seed sold by agro-dealers.
\end_layout

