\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "7 Conclusion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study examines how aggregated peer ratings of seed performance affect farmer beliefs,
 agro-dealer choice,
 and agro-dealer behavior.
 The intervention could operate through three channels:
 correcting pessimistic or imprecise beliefs among farmers (belief updating),
 helping farmers identify and switch to better-performing dealers (dealer sorting),
 or inducing agro-dealers to invest in seed preservation (supply-side accountability).
 Using a randomized experiment,
 we evaluate the effects of this intervention on a range of farmer and agro-dealer outcomes and distinguish between these channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that the intervention leads farmers to update their beliefs and improves their perceptions of seed performance.
 In an exploratory analysis,
 we find that effects on perceptions are larger among farmers without prior purchasing experience,
 consistent with the model's prediction that farmers facing greater uncertainty about seed performance weight the peer signal more heavily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As farmers update their beliefs,
 the intervention increases their adoption of high-yielding maize varieties purchased from agro-dealers and leads to higher productivity and improved harvest outcomes.
 The combination of positive treatment effects on perceptions,
 adoption,
 and productivity suggests that prior beliefs were overly pessimistic relative to seed performance and that the seeds accessed through agro-dealers performed favorably compared with outside options.
 Consistent with the model,
 these findings indicate that aggregated peer ratings can move farmers’ beliefs closer to the performance of seed sold through agro-dealers,
 shifting adoption decisions toward the welfare-optimal level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This finding is consistent with existing evidence.
 Studies from fertilizer markets show that farmers often underestimate input quality relative to objective measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and recent work on maize seed in Uganda suggests that farmers’ perceptions may be more pessimistic than warranted by measured performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Insights from psychology and economics further suggest that negative information tends to be more salient,
 spreads faster,
 and receives disproportionate weight in social learning under noisy production conditions,
 which can skew belief formation toward pessimism
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "neg_bias,vaish2008not,10.1257/aer.100.1.35,hornik2015information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the supply side,
 the evidence is more limited.
 We find no improvement in seed handling,
 storage practices,
 or objective seed quality.
 There is suggestive evidence of some changes in service provision and signaling professionalism,
 but these effects are less robust than the demand-side findings and are not central to our interpretation.
 While we find some evidence that the intervention induces switching between agro-dealers,
 this switching is not directed toward higher-rated dealers,
 providing little support for dealer sorting as a primary channel.
 The pattern of results —
 positive effects on perceptions and adoption,
 undirected switching and no improvement in seed quality —
 points to belief updating as the primary impact pathway.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study highlights the potential for aggregated peer information to improve market outcomes in environments where buyers face uncertainty about input performance and learning from own experience and social networks is limited.
 By pooling experiences from multiple users,
 such signals can help farmers form more accurate beliefs about input performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More broadly,
 our findings suggest that the primary channel through which crowd-sourced information platforms affect market outcomes depends on the nature of the binding constraint.
 In markets where consumers already participate but face difficulty choosing among sellers,
 the main channel is sorting —
 as documented in the online reviews literature.
 In markets where the binding constraint is participation itself —
 as in our setting,
 where many farmers do not engage with agro-dealers due to uncertainty about seed performance —
 the main channel is belief updating at the extensive margin.
 This distinction has implications for how clearinghouse systems should be designed:
 when the goal is to increase market participation rather than improve matching,
 broad dissemination to non-participants matters more than fine-grained seller rankings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These findings have implications for policy and practice.
 Aggregating and disseminating users’ experiences can improve market outcomes when quality assurance systems are weak or imperfect,
 offering a decentralized complement that does not rely on strong institutional capacity.
 Peer ratings help farmers form more accurate beliefs,
 reducing the barrier to adoption.
 There is also suggestive evidence that the accountability pressure from ratings may incentivize service improvements among agro-dealers,
 though this channel requires further investigation.
 For private actors,
 including agro-dealers and seed companies,
 experience-based feedback mechanisms can build credibility and strengthen market engagement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the time of implementation,
 limited smartphone access required an offline design.
 As digital access expands among smallholder farmers,
 similar systems could be implemented through online platforms,
 offering lower costs,
 broader reach,
 and greater scalability,
 although this remains to be tested.
\end_layout

